body:
Currently it's not possible to fire up a runspace instance in .NET Core. As soon as the .Open() method is called, the program gets stuck and errors after some time.

### Steps to reproduce

Corresponding code:
```
Runspace rs;
var pspi = new PowerShellProcessInstance();
pspi.Process.StartInfo.FileName = @"C:\Windows\System32\WindowsPowerShell\v1.0\powershell.exe";
pspi.Process.Start();
rs = RunspaceFactory.CreateOutOfProcessRunspace(new TypeTable(new string[0]), pspi);
rs.Open();

using (PowerShell powershell = PowerShell.Create()) {
    powershell.Runspace = rs;
    powershell.AddScript(<some code>);
    var output = powershell.Invoke();
}
```

### Expected behavior
Open the runspace instance like in .NET Framework.


### Actual behavior

The following Error occurs. 

```
System.Management.Automation.Remoting.PSRemotingTransportException HResult=0x80131501 
Nachricht = The background process reported an error with the following message: D 
Quelle = System.Management.Automation
```


### Environment data

- .NET Core 5.0 Console Application
- Packages: Microsoft.PowerShell.SDK & System.Management.Automation (up-to-date)
- Windows 10 Pro

### Summary of the new feature / enhancement

The `$PSDefaultParameterValues` preference variable allows presetting parameter values not just with static values, but also _dynamically_, via _script blocks_.

The script block is currently passed a single argument that is a custom object containing the _names_ of the already-bound parameters, but it would be useful to also pass their _values_, so as to determine the preset value based on the specific argument values in the call at hand.

A real-world example, from [this Stack Overflow question](https://stackoverflow.com/q/68954591/45375):

For `New-Item`, `-Force` should be preset to `$true` only if the item being created is a _directory_ (so that a preexisting directory is returned rather than causing an error).

To that end, the already-bound value of the `-ItemType` parameter must be inspected, but it currently isn't available, necessitating the following - incomplete - workaround:

```powershell
$PSDefaultParameterValues = @{
  'New-Item:Force' = { 
    ($false, $true)[
      $args.BoundParameters.Contains('ItemType') -and 
      # !! Incomplete workaround: examine the raw invocation command line.
      (Get-PSCallStack)[1].Position.Text -match '\bDirectory\b'
    ]
  }
}
```


### Proposed technical implementation details (optional)

Add a `.BoundParameterValues` property containing dictionary to the `[pscustomobject]` instance passed to the script block that allows retrieving the bound parameter _values_ by name, which would enable the following - robust - solution:

```powershell
$PSDefaultParameterValues = @{
  'New-Item:Force' = { 
    ($false, $true)[
      $args.BoundParameterValues['ItemType'] -eq 'Directory'
    ]
  }
}
```

Note: Arguably, it is `.BoundParameters` itself that should contain this dictionary, but this would amount to a breaking change.

Here's the structure of the object currently being passed, using sample values from an invocation such as `New-Item -ItemType Directory foo`:

```none
class PSCustomObject
{
  BoundParameters =
    [
      ItemType
      Path
    ]

  BoundPositionalParameters =
    [
      Path
    ]

  BoundDefaultParameters =
    [
    ]
}
```

Note: `BoundParameters` and `BoundPositionalParameters` only contain _names_ (`[string]`s); I presume `BoundDefaultParameters` would too, but it's unclear to me under what conditions it gets filled; parameters with default values in the target command's parameter declaration apparently do _not_ show up here.

### Summary of the new feature / enhancement

I have found some alternatives in the [discussion](https://github.com/PowerShell/PowerShell/issues/13004).
But, If I want to output an error message, which method should I use, I don't seem to have found an alternative in PowerShell.

`out IList errors`

```
public Collection Invoke(string script, IEnumerable input, out IList errors)
{
        if (_disposed == true)
        {
            throw PSTraceSource.NewObjectDisposedException("runspace");
        }
        if (script == null)
        {
            throw PSTraceSource.NewArgumentNullException("script");
        }

        Pipeline p = _runspace.CreatePipeline(script);
        Collection<PSObject> output = p.Invoke(input);
        // 2004/06/30-JonN was ReadAll() which was non-blocking
        errors = p.Error.NonBlockingRead();
        return output;
}
```

